Citations
Date:  28/10/1933
Source:  Press, The
Author:
Vol / Page:  17
Edition:
Quote:  Hatter. One who works and camps by himself. Originally a miner's expression, no doubt from the saying of a man without relations that he had `all his family under his hat'. Archdeacon  Harper derived the word from `mad as a hatter' (Letters, p. 143). The word is in general use on stations. H.'s billy, tent, etc., one just large enough for one man. ([1898 Morris Austral-English])
Notes:  Acland Glossary

Date:  0/0/1898
Source:  Austral English
Author:  MORRiS
Vol / Page:  193
Edition:
Quote:  Hatter, ... (1) A solitary miner - miner who works without a mate partner: sc. one who has everything under his own hat.
